english:
  title: An Edict Denying Four Requests for Retirement
  author: Choi Yu-cheong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have heard that a prime minister's advancement and retreat do not depend upon his own circumstances alone, and that a ruler's success or failure rests entirely upon his great ministers. Consider how without sound limbs a man cannot be whole, and without harmony between yin and yang there can be no proper year—thus we see how urgently ruler and minister must rely upon each other.

    You have now requested your retirement many times, and I too have urged you to stay with all my heart. To advance with propriety and retire with righteousness may be the noble aspiration of a worthy man, yet should we not share both hardship and joy? Is this not also the way of a benevolent sovereign? Moreover, you have become the elder statesman of this generation through inherited loyalty, unmoved by fortune or misfortune, ever steadfast in your duty to support and elevate the throne. When the people's hearts hung in balance, you eliminated the traitors; when the nation trembled on the brink, you secured the dynasty. Through your hand, the altars of state have been restored to peace and the ancestral temple brought to blessing. Your great achievements and illustrious deeds yield nothing to the ancients—why should I begrudge you high office and noble title today?

    I am now redoubling my care over the ten thousand affairs of state, and we shall together illuminate our common virtue. Let us heed the lessons of the past and cultivate the future, strengthen our armies and granaries to repel the barbarians, and revive the rites and music to establish order in the realm. My mind is fixed upon this, my resolve deepened—yet you would abandon these labors and turn away, forsaking your distant counsel for the nation's sake?

    Though a warm chamber and cool pavilion may offer their pleasures, the office of prime minister cannot long remain vacant. I ask you to consider the greater good and not leave me without one upon whom to rely.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Four Requests' (四度) refer to the minister's repeated petitions to retire from office. This edict is the sovereign's fourth refusal, attempting to persuade him to remain in service to the state.
    - The 'two breaths' (二氣) and 'limbs' (四肢) are classical metaphors for cosmic and governmental harmony respectively.
